  "detailedRequirements": "<p><strong>Detailed Requirements</strong></p>\n\n<p>We have previously developed a concept workflow using the Amazon Simple Workflow service, see <a href=\"http://community.topcoder.com/tc?module=ProjectDetail&amp;pj=30042878\">this</a>&nbsp;to understand what the workflow does.</p>\n\n<p>Now&nbsp;<span style=\"color:rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family:arial,sans-serif\">we want to be able to auto-scale (Amazon) Elastic Beanstalk instances based on the size of an activity queue in a workflow of the (Amazon) Simple Workflow Services. &nbsp;Elastic Beanstalk will start up/shut down a new VM given an AMI and optional program data. &nbsp;So the idea is that we want these EB instances to run the code that processes the activity in the workflow. &nbsp;The code already developed in the previous F2F does that. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style=\"color:rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family:arial,sans-serif\">You can set it up and it will process items that come in to the queue. &nbsp;It is not currently set up as an EB instance, just ready to install on a VM to process the queue. &nbsp;But in production the queue will go from 0 to 500+ very quickly and then back down to 0 once everything is processed. &nbsp;So EB will start up multiple instances to handle items in the queue based on how big the queue is - and then shut them down when they are no longer needed. The client wishes to use the auto-scaling feature of EB to do this. &nbsp;The auto-scaling feature uses metrics from Cloud Watch to do this. &nbsp;However, we can&#39;t find the right metric to use.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style=\"color:rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family:arial,sans-serif\">So we need someone to investigate this and come up with a solution that uses Amazon&#39;s services to do what we need.</span></p>\n\n<p>For submission we need a document describing in details how this can be done. And we&#39;ll need the winner to help setup and test the solution on provided EB instance(s).</p>\n\n<p>Please post any questions you may have to the forum and good luck!</p>\n",
